Histogram¶

plt.show()
In [12]:
# Seaborn     
# Observe the plot look & feel
# shape is different due to No. of bins
sns.histplot(data = df, x='Length')    
plt.title('Histogram')
plt.show()
In [16]:
# Seaborn     
# Observe the plot look & feel and shape is same.
sns.histplot(data = df, x='Length', bins =10)    
plt.title('Histogram')
plt.show()
In [19]:
sns.displot(data=df,x='Length', bins=10)
plt.title('Histogram')
plt.show()

displot¶

displot is the distribution plot. there are 4 distribution plots which you can make just by this single command.
In [20]:
sns.displot(data=df,x='Length', bins=10, hue = 'Operator')
plt.title('Histogram')
plt.show()
In [23]:
sns.displot(data=df,x='Length', bins=10, col = 'Operator')
plt.show()

KDE plot¶

KDE plot - and KDE is Kernal density estimate, gives us smooth line
Displot is the rug plot
In [27]:
sns.displot(data=df,x='Length', rug = 'true', kind = 'kde')
plt.show()
In [50]:
sns.displot(data=df,x='Length', rug = 'true', kind = 'kde', hue = 'Operator')
plt.show()

ecdf kind - empirical distribution function (commonly also called an empirical Cumulative Distribution Function, eCDF)¶

In [51]:
sns.displot(data=df,x='Length', rug = 'true', kind = 'ecdf')
plt.show()
In [52]:
sns.displot(data=df,x='Length', rug = True, kde = True, kind = 'hist')
plt.show()
In [53]:
sns.displot(data=df,x='Length', y = 'Width')
plt.show()
In [54]:
sns.displot(data=df,x='Length', y = 'Width', kind='kde')
plt.show()

Catplot group of plots (Category plots)¶

Catplots - 8 -kinds categorical scatterplots: kind:strip kind:swarm categorical distributio plots: kind:box kind:violin kind:boxen categorical estimate plots: kind:point kind:bar kind:count

Categorical scatterplots:

stripplot() (with kind="strip"; the default)

swarmplot() (with kind="swarm")
Categorical distribution plots:

boxplot() (with kind="box")

violinplot() (with kind="violin")

boxenplot() (with kind="boxen")
Categorical estimate plots:

pointplot() (with kind="point")

barplot() (with kind="bar")

countplot() (with kind="count")

Relplot group of plots (REL = Relationship)¶

Relplot is related to the relationship between two variables. We will be looking at -

  1. scatterplot
  2. line plot.
In [73]:
